Base Buy grid shows Feb + Mar as separate columns. The unified pipeline averages to a representative-week figure (approximately 50% of raw grid totals). National spots are replicated to all 11 DMAs in Tab 3.

Day/Hour Expansion

"How compressed schedules become individual time slots"

Raw vendor data from Tab 1: Raw DataExpanded data gets national replication in Tab 3: National Replication

How This Tab Works

Compressed schedules (e.g., MTuWThF 9-12PM) are expanded into individual day × hour cells. Spots, impressions, and dollars are DIVIDED — not multiplied — to conserve totals.

→ Tab 3: How expanded data gets national replication

Assumptions Applied
Daypart Boundaries: 9 rangesWeekend Days: Sa, Su
Division Principle: 100 spots, MTuWThF, 9AM-12PM → 100 ÷ (5 days × 3 hours) = 6.67 spots/cell
Spots are DIVIDED not MULTIPLIED — row sums must equal input totals.
Row Explosion: 451 raw rows → 16,012 unified rows (35.5x expansion) ✓ Conservation Verified

Division principle preserved: spots, dollars, and impressions are conserved through the expansion process.

Note: Day/hour expansion conserves totals per source. National replication (Tab 3) adds spots to all 11 DMAs, so pipeline-wide totals are higher than raw input totals.

National Replication

"How national buys become 11 local markets"

Expanded schedules from Tab 2: Day/Hour ExpansionDerived columns added in Tab 4: Derived Columns

How This Tab Works

National buys air in all 11 CA markets. Spots stay the same (ad airs nationally). Impressions and dollars are weighted by DMA population share. Population is also used in 5 other downstream calculations.

→ Tab 4: Derived columns added to expanded data

Assumptions Applied
CA National Share: 24.5%US Hispanic Total: 47,500,000DMA Populations: 11 markets
National Spot → CA Share (24.5%) → 11 Markets (pop. weighted)
Key Distinction: Each national row’s spots are replicated to every market. Total spots per market may vary if national line items differ. Impressions and dollars are WEIGHTED by DMA population share.

Population Usage Map — 6 Downstream Stages

DMA population drives 6 different calculations across the pipeline. Click tab links to see each in context.

1
National Allocation Tab 3
Market_Imps = National_Imps × CA_Share × (DMA_Pop / Total_CA_Pop)
LA gets 44.8% of national impressions; Palm Springs gets 1.7%
2
GRP Calculation Tab 7
GRPs = (Impressions / DMA_Population) × 100
100K imps in LA (4,366,400 pop) = 2.3 GRPs; in Palm Springs (165,500 pop) = 60.4 GRPs
3
BBD Reach Ceilings Tab 7
reach = min(raw_reach, DMA_ceiling)
Fresno: 55%, Chico-Redding: 44%, LA: 53%
4
Frequency Derivation Tab 7
Frequency = GRPs / (Reach% × 100)
LA (large pop) has lower frequency than Palm Springs (small pop) for same impression volume
5
Station Deduplication Tab 7
adjusted_reach = reach × dedup_factor × dma_adjustment
LA: 3 stations factor 0.78 × DMA adj 0.97
6
Cross-Media Overlap Tab 7
combined_reach uses population as denominator for overlap resolution
TV reach + Radio reach - (TV × Radio × duplication_factor)

Derived Columns

"What we calculate from the expanded data"

Replicated data from Tab 3: National ReplicationAggregated into market summary in Tab 5: Unified Summary

How This Tab Works

Derived columns are calculated from expanded data. 30-second is the optimal ad unit. Eq30s converts all lengths to a common unit with symmetric penalties for non-30s spots.

→ Tab 5: Aggregated market summary

Assumptions Applied
Length Weights: :1s=0.05, :5s=0.15, :7s=0.25, :10s=0.4, :15s=0.75, :30s=1.0, :60s=0.75Daypart Boundaries: 9 ranges

Eq30s Formula

Eq30s = Spot_Count × (Length ÷ 30) × Length_Weight
Weight Philosophy: Symmetric Penalties Around :30s

LengthWeight× Duration Factor= Eq30sStatus
:15s0.75× 0.50.375Penalized (too short)
:30s1.0× 1.01.0OPTIMAL BASELINE
:60s0.75× 2.01.5Penalized (attention drops)
7 rows
LengthAd unit length in secondsWeightAttention factor: 1.0 for :30, penalized for othersEq30s (1 spot)Result of (Length/30) × Weight for 1 spotFormula
:1s0.050.0021 x (1/30) x 0.05
:5s0.150.0251 x (5/30) x 0.15
:7s0.250.0581 x (7/30) x 0.25
:10s0.40.1331 x (10/30) x 0.4
:15s0.750.3751 x (15/30) x 0.75
:30s1.01.01 x (30/30) x 1.0
:60s0.751.51 x (60/30) x 0.75

How This Tab Works

The BBD (Beta-Binomial Distribution) model converts cumulative GRPs into unduplicated reach. This is where viewer overlap is resolved. Frequency = GRPs ÷ (Reach% × 100). Each market has DMA-specific reach ceilings.

→ Tab 8: How frequency zones drive optimization actions

Assumptions Applied
TV BBD: =1.0, =5.0, ceiling=0.5Radio BBD: =0.7, =4.0, ceiling=0.55Cross-Media: duplication=0.6, ceiling=0.65Frequency Target: 7.0x weeklyDecay Rate: =0.25
TV_Reach = 1 − (1 + TV_GRPs/100 × β/(α+β))^(−α)  [capped at DMA ceiling]
Radio_Reach = same formula with radio params
Combined = TV_Reach + Radio_Reach − (TV_Reach × Radio_Reach × Duplication)
Adjusted = min(Combined, combined_ceiling) × Station_Dedup_Factor

BBD Reach Curves

Full Calculation Chain: Los Angeles
1 Total Impressions (from Tab 5): 46,791,440
2 DMA Population: 4,366,400 | TV ceiling=0.53 | Stations=1
3 TV GRPs = 1071.6, Radio GRPs = 314.9
4 TV Reach = BBD(TV_GRPs, ceiling=0.53) = 0.53
5 Radio Reach = BBD(Radio_GRPs, ceiling=0.55) = 0.55
6 Combined = TV + Radio - (TV × Radio × 0.6) overlap formula
7 Adjusted = min(Combined, 0.65) × Dedup(1.0) = 46.0%
8 Frequency = (1071.6 + 314.9) / (Reach% × 100) = 23.3x → SEVERE_OVER

Per-Market Frequency (Before Optimization)

NOT summable — accounts for viewer overlap via ceiling.FrequencyGRPs / (Reach% × 100). Average exposures per reached person.ZoneUNDER <3x, OPTIMAL 3-7x, OVER 7-12x, SEVERE_OVER >12x

How This Tab Works

The optimizer reduces frequency in over-target markets by cutting spots. Priority: Sponsorship first (most flexible), then Base Buy, then National (least flexible). Within each type, cut_first dayparts are reduced before protected dayparts.
